    <text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1937-12-14T21:10:00-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1937-12-14T21:10:00-05:00" n="645"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d645">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">394.115 Panay/70: Telegram</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">The Commander in Chief of the United States Asiatic Fleet</hi>
                        (<persName type="from">
                        <hi rend="italic">Yarnell</hi>
                    </persName>) <hi rend="italic">to the Chief of Naval Operations</hi> (<persName
                        type="to">
                        <hi rend="italic">Leahy</hi>
                    </persName>)<note n="79" xml:id="d645fn79">Copy transmitted to the Department by
                        the Navy Department.</note>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">[<placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Shanghai</hi>
                        </placeName>,] <date calendar="gregorian" when="1937-12-15T10:10:00+08:00"
                            >December 15, 1937—10:10 a.m.</date>
                        <lb/>[Received December 15—1 a.m.]</dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>0015. H.M.S. <hi rend="italic">Bee</hi> reports first group <hi rend="italic"
                        >Panay</hi> survivors arrived 2350 Tuesday, remainder at 0200 today. Two
                    coffins will be brought out at 0900 today. As far as can be learned all persons
                    accounted for. Following stretcher cases: Lt. Comdr. J. J. Hughes, Lt. A. F.
                    Anders, K. J. Rice (E.M. 3d), J. H. Lang (C.Q.M.), C. H. Birk (E.M. 1st), A. A.
                    Kozak (M.M. 2d), E. W. G. Hulsebus (Cox’n), P. D. Ziegler <pb facs="0510"
                        n="502" xml:id="pg_502"/> (S.C. 3d), C. S. Schroyer (Sea’n 1st), N. L. Davis
                    (F 1st), Mr. Gassie, Embassy clerk. MacDonald,<note n="80" xml:id="d645fn80"
                        >Malcolm MacDonald, correspondent of the London <hi rend="italic"
                        >Times</hi>.</note> correspondent, among first group survivors, reports <hi
                        rend="italic">Panay</hi> hit about 1350 12th by bomb from great height. Ship
                    abandoned at 1405. Before vessel sank was machine gunned by two Japanese Army
                    motor boats whose crews boarded about 1554 and left before vessel sank. Colors
                    were flying and clearly visible during whole time. <hi rend="italic">Oahu</hi>
                    radio was out of commission 10 hours, now back in commission.</p>
            </div>
